nce. By examining the key points of divergencefrom and adaptation of his Italian, Latin and French sources and analogues, the author identifes the specific ways in which Wyatt reformed those sources in order to comment upon the lability of Tudor diplomacy and the political machinations at home and abroad which informed it - as well as the personal cost to Wyatt himself. The volume also identifies Wyatt's innovations and his debts, so redressing earlier interpretations of Wyatt's work which ignored its translative ontology. Through noting Wyatt's specific alterations and ameliorations, it allows a clearer image of his poetics to develop. Dr William T. Rossiter is Senior Lecturer in Medieval and Early Modern EnglishLiterature at the University of East Anglia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnglish poetryxHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aDiplomat.  aEuropean Poetry.  aLiterary Analysis.  aPolitical Machinations.  aPower.  aThomas Wyatt.  aTranslation.  aTudor Diplomacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782043577?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782043577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782043577/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles